caption: Great Great Great food!!! Fried chicken and drunken noodles are a must try. Do yourself a favor and have their food when in Portland. You won't be disappointed!
Portland is a pleasant surprise for lovers of Asian food and honey paw is one such place. Great food and staff!
Loved the heated patio area. Everything felt very clean, separated, and safe. Plus, the food was delicious!

I had a good experience at their sister restaurant next door and was in the mood for Thai food so tried Honey Paw. The order was ready quick and was a good size portion for the price. Smoked Lamb Khao Soi was prepared very well. I’ve never had duck taste so moist, and I would definitely recommend that dish.
Food not good as expected

The food was great, but I’m docking a star for not updating the app to notify us when our order was ready. We would have waited in our car for even longer if we weren’t hungry. Our food was cold when we popped it open.

Incredible - a MUST go. The flavours, the quality and the freshness of everything was unbeatable.  Apps: Started with kimchi, easily the best kimchi I’ve ever had. Entrees: Biang Biang and Smoked Lamb Khao Soi Both so delicious and the best Asian fashion I’ve had in the US. I’ll let the photos speak for themselves!

I don't give 5 star reviews lightly or often, but I'm writing this as I sit here digesting. Service was attentive while not being over bearing. Food was prepared quickly but not rushed.  Kimchi was zesty.  The Khao Soi smoked lamb extremely tender and the mix of crispy and soft noodles was perfect, lime not required.  Biang Biang noodles were fat, long and still chewy. Hot Szechuan pepper braised beef melted in mouth..  We are only here for another day, but may come back.
I am a local, fortunate enough to live a block away. The smoked lamb khao soi absolutely deserves the James Beard award...and to think...only a block away

Amazing. Fun fusion in some classics and great flavor all around! Can’t wait for them to be indoors again but they made it work in the tent! The hand pulled noodles and ramen were both to die for and warmed ya to the bone on the meantime :) worth a visit!
This place was one of our favorite restaurants we visited in Portland. delicious food and unique menu, like nothing we'd had before. We liked it much better than Fore Street.
Delicious! The Biang Biang was too heavily flavored and very small. The Mee Goreng was yummy
Some of the most creative and delicious food around!
Fantastic unique food with great service. Is pricier than I would like but you definitely get quality over quantity at this place.
This place is phenomenal. I always see people in line for Eventide but I think this place is even better. The food is great!

Service: meh Food: wings were good, served my friend's meal 20 minutes before mine, told me the "woks we're backed up" then served my entree on a bread plate ($18) as an afterthought and then to top it off the noodles (main part of my order) weren't cooked through.

The food was delicious and so was the service. I’d have to say I was really disappointed with the portion sizes as they were quite small for food that was expensive. I got the biang biang which was very good however it only came with 4 (large) noodles (trust me not that filling) and 4 small pieces of beef (very small) for the cost of 18.00 plus tax. If you’re going to this restaurant very hungry, that meal will not be enough.
Khao soi is very good, though perhaps a touch salty. The honey salted soft serve is outstanding, though.
Just perfection. Koi Soi - the closest thai version you can get, Broccoli, fried bread, just get them! Won't regret. House beer is fantastic.
Delicious! Amazing. Incredible! Awesome! Can’t say enough about the meal My wife and I just had! My wife says: “Even more amazing every bite in”

Incredible meal! Our sever Sara T killed it with every recommendation! Wings incredible, Khao Soi to die for. An absolute must for Portland dining.
The flavor profiles in their dishes were unbelievable. Nice outdoor seating and the food warmed me up on a chilly day. Also, the best kimchi I think I’ve ever had!

Arguably, the best dinner spot in Portland. And the Khao Soi is one of the best dishes I’ve ever had! If you’re debating on where to eat and are craving comfort food this is the place to be. Don’t think it gets better than this! Loved it so much & will absolutely be back again. (Better than Eventide)
Everything is really good. My favorite is the Smoked Lamb Khao Soi.

Super tasty food and a great spot. Definitely coming back.
I would put this food alongside any you find in New York or San Francisco. Thoughtful, detailed, and powerful.

caption: Blown away by every single dish we ordered here. The quality and presentation definitely warrants higher prices. The ramen noodles were nice and chewy.

Absolutely delicious food with great service, friendly and knowledgeable waiters. It was certainly some of the best Asian food we’ve tried. We ordered the lobster ceviche, bread with brown butter, tuna tartar, lobster dumplings and from the entrees ramen and another spicy entree dish. All were so delicious. Still talking about it. Sake was great as usual. The honey ice cream was so goood. Highly recommend!

Honey Paw was excellent.  Due to COVID19, all dining was outside, and Honey Paw did a great job.  Great outdoor seating, well distanced, every staff member was not only wearing masks, but doing so correctly.  The food and cocktails were all amazing.  The lobster ceviche was some of the best bites I've ever had, and this is the only place I've seen outside of Boston to offer biang biang noodles.  Aside from the ceviche and biang biang noodles we got lobster ravioli and lamb curry, (as well as a few cocktails).  It was all delicious, well presented and a well worth the reasonable prices.

Food and drinks were great. My only two comments would be that the food should be served at the same time for the guests in the same party, my husband's plate arrived almost 10 mins before mine. Also the host wasn't too friendly.
The lobster wontons and khao soi are really extraordinary!

Our greeter was a solid C+ in his friendliness. Nothing mean or nasty about him. All of the right words were there but nothing heartfelt. All fine, and I don’t blame him since we were one of many waiting (over 45 minutes) to try this restaurant.  Our waitress was very friendly. We sat outdoors with everyone else in this Covid world we now live in. We ordered the lobster dumplings. They were okay. We next got the mapo tofu. The sauce was way too much and the flavors were a mixture of everything but the kitchen sink. This description seemed to be the theme of the night there as their next dish, me gorang was just an overpowering mix of every herb you could think of. The biang biang noodles were over sauced and over flavored too. The best dish of the night was the dessert.  If you want a nice soft serve cone with just the right  amount of sweetness, then you should come here.
A really enjoyable Portland meal. The Khao Soi is stellar, as is the soft serve yogurt.
One of the best spots in Portland, there wings and deserts are amazing!!

We had an amazing meal here. Started with the tuna tartar special and fried bread - both very good. My boyfriend had the Khao Soi which was super rich but delicious. The star of the show was the honey soft serve - the honeycomb was the most delicious thing I’ve ever eaten 😍our server was friendly and very knowledgeable. Friendly staff. Gave great recommendations if you're unsure what you get. They have daily specials. Everything is Asian fusion inspired and has great flavors that complements without being overpowering. Kimchi Ramen has just the right amount of spice. And perfect for a cold winter night.

Everything was delicious. Great beer selection and the noodles were just the right comfort on a cold night. Loooved the funky desserts - we got carmelized onion soft serve with honeycomb crisps and chocolate hardshell to top it off.

This place was phenomenal! The drinks, service, food and desert were all exceptional. I highly recommend the lobster  wontons. They were delicious, a good portion of lobster meat with a very tasty lemongrass curry broth.

We had a lovely time dining at The Honey Paw. We went two days before Christmas and was pretty busy. We had a bit of a wait for 4 people but it was so worth it. The food and service was wonderful. The appetizer portions are a pretty decent size. We had the wings, crudo, and charred cabbage (which was insanely good). For dinner we had the lo main and Ramen bowl. All were delicious. We are looking forward to going back!

The interior is very bright. There is a large chalkboard with the daily specials. There are old menus from Asian restaurants framed and up on the wall and made me feel like they were trying to be more "Asian" with the menus. Service is fast and the servers are kind.  We ordered off the happy hour menu. We ordered the Zambino which had a cinnamon flavor. It's good, but I was not a big fan because it had the burn of alcohol at the end of the drink. We ordered the bao and the order only came with one bao. It was pan-fried and extremely greasy and salty. The flavor came from the shredded pickled vegetables inside the bun and the pork had no flavor. The wings were decent, but nothing special. The fried gyoza was covered in red chili oil and that is what it tasted like. The fry bread with uni butter was light. I did not taste any hint of uni in the uni butter, so I was disappointed. The honey soft serve is really good and had just the right amount of sweetness, but the chocolate shell tasted cheap. I think it would be better without the chocolate. The chocolate peppermint is good and had a decent amount of brownie bits at the bottom, but there was nothing special about it.  Overall, 4 stars for the honey soft serve and service and 3 stars for the rest of the happy hour menu. The food is okay, but nothing jumps out except for the soft serve.
Delicious! Fun, casual and interesting food combos for Asian Fusion. Great for small plates, amazing drinks and Sake!

I would drive back to Portland just to have those two dishes. When you are in Portland, this is an absolute must.

I found the Honey Paw to be a decently over priced asian amalgamation over asian fusion. The atmosphere is cramped and can get quite loud. If your looking for seating you can converse in with more than one other person, that is going to be difficult. The main portions of seating are bar style, or these very tiny two person tables.  If you get the right food it can be tasty, but most of it is done in the typical 'fancy' resturants small plates style which I almost never find to be worth it bar a couple exceptions.  The food i had often felt close but not quite right to the original sources, and I would have prefered to just go somewhere that served them closer to the original styles.  I found the kimchi to be too vinegar in flavor, and didnt feel like the gochujang flavor didnt show through. Its hard to go wrong with what is essentially savory fried dough, but i feel it was too expensive. The miso ramen was decent. Im not sure how you can make a miso broth not salty enough though. Its hard to mess up ramen in miso with veg and a pork belly. But to be honest, I would not come here again, nor would i reccomend it to anyone. The staff was lovely but the food just isnt worth it.
The rare beef appetizer was so good we ordered a second.  The poke was OK, but everything else we ordered was excellent.

Food tasted fine but the real issue is the price for the serving size. I got pork belly ramen and received only one slice of pork belly for $18. The SO got a crab and pork dish that had literally no crab. Or at the very least, not a single taste of crab. Again it tasted good it just felt like both dishes short changed us. Will not return given the expansive food scene in Portland.
The food was excellent. Good service. Small portions. Be prepared to sit at the bar or a communal table.

Hipster noodle shop with some decent dishes but lack in authenticity and portion.  Our khao soi was very flavorful, but unfortunately the other two noodle dishes were lackluster. The miso ramen was tiny, and bland. The BiangBiang Noodle smelled really great, but was quite overcooked and was overall uninspired.  Overall, the three dishes came out to about $64 dollars and we felt like we just ate three appetizers rather than main dishes. I think in the future, larger portion sizes and focus on amping up the flavor would bring us back to the Honey Paw.

Sitting at a window seat, listening to Bikini Kill and eating food that tastes as punk as the music I’m listening to is the culmination of our visit to Maine. If you aren’t an adventurous eater don’t go here. If you aren’t excited by all things flavor, and food that you undeniably cannot cook at home, this is not the place for you. If you’re sensitive to spice, and picky in anyway, keep walking. You can find your lobster rolls next door (no shame).  If you love a dizzying array of ingredients and a compilation of complex flavors this is where you should be. Casual cool service, and family style seating enhance the experience. Check it out. Great service and atmosphere, but based on the two items we ordered I have to say the food is a bit hit or miss. We shared the smoked lamb noodle bowl and the 1/2 fried chicken. The lamb was great. lots of meat in super rich flavorful broth. it comes with fermented daikon radish though and that was a bit much. Lamb can be quite rich and gamey which i like but paired with that funky daikon it was just too much. I actually wish there had been more noodles and broth and less of everything else. Next was the fried chicken which we were told takes a bit longer which is normal and completely understandable. The chicken comes out cuts up in pieces with a huge skillet of cornbread. The breast meat was fine very crispy with good flavor but the leg and thigh however were under cooked and still pink in middle. Couldn't eat. The cornbread was weird. it was very greasy with a giant ball of butter or coconut oil or something in the middle. It was also quite dense and again was just too much with the chicken.  i know how popular and well loved this place is so maybe we just had an off night.

After a whirlwind food tour through Portland, I can confidently say Honey Paw was hands down my favorite experience. Firstly, while I'm sure there is sometimes a wait, my bf and I didn't have to put our names on a list for a 1 hour+ wait to dine here. The decor was trendy but still inspired by elements of Maine. We ordered the MATSUTAKE DONBURI and SMOKED LAMB KHAO SOI (excuse the caps, copied from their menu). The mushroom dish was both hot and cold and was one of the most elegant dishes I've ever had. My fave was the pate like mousse on the tamago and the little tempura crisps in their rice seasoning. The curry noodle dish was also delicious! At first, it came out lukewarm but the kitchen quickly remade a fresh bowl for me. I love their use of the mustard greens and the broth wasn't too salty (as many "ramens" are or too heavy). The noodles were also perfectly cooked. As a small apology for the mistake with my dish, they brought out a sample of their banana ice cream. Holy cow it was SO good and fresh, served with chocolate and pie crust. My favorite overall dining experience in Portland because the environment was welcoming, each dish had something special, and my mouth is literally watering as I write this review now. I would make the 2 hour drive any weekend to eat here again.

The food at honeypaw is excellent.  There’s something about it that’s just so delicious— a perfect spice level, a perfect crunch level, a perfect sauce level. I’ve been back a half dozen times, and the food, service, interior, are all five star worthy.  So I’m now begging you honeypaw PLEASE, change your seating plan or incorporate sound absorption into your decoration. Sitting in the restaurant is a little like sitting in a wood chipper. It is SO LOUD inside.  Extremely tall ceilings, cement floor, and seating that doesn’t allow you to interact with anyone more than the person directly next to you makes the dining experience unfortunately uncomfortable. Maybe I’ll be able to update my review when I go back with noise-canceling headphones, but until then the assault on my ears unfortunately outweighs the delight of my tastebuds.
